<br>
What Intra is describing, is to completely remove any pretense of the RPG, and make it into purely a Technical Event - 'Can we figure out the necessary sequence to prevail in encounter x?  What kind of DPS is required?  What exact mix of levels and classes is needed?  What is the minimum we can do it with?'<br>
<br>
To enter a room and say &quot;This room is for all intents and purposes, your World - this is no longer Norrath, its just a Testing Chamber.  You will now face encounters that are designed to challenge your knowledge of the 'game physics' and rules of EQ, and how quickly and accurately you can apply them under pressure.  If you are successful, you will advance to more difficult encounters, there we will CHANGE the rules of the game, making you work with less resources to see if you can still pull it off.&quot; - is not my idea of a fun MMORPG.<br>
<br>
Not to mention the fact that as you continuously make the conditions more restrictive, and therefore less tolerant of any deviation from perfection, you also ultimately limit success to those whpo have a) the time to practice constantly, b) the best and faster Computers, and c) the best and fastest broadband internet connection.<br>
<br>
Sounds more like something for a single player off line game to me.  In order to be mildly entertaining for an Online Game at least PvP would make tactics something more that just being able to figure out the mathematics of Aggro and DPS to silly levels.  :-p <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uellywig.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ellywig</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 670<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/28/02 9:23:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2203.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A zone of rooms</span><hr size=1> As a tactical simulation, perhaps offered by some powerful order?<br>
<br>
&quot;We are the Guardians of the Nineteenth Chalice. You have come before us to proclaim your worthiness/seek our guidance/endure the Tests of Gnork/etc. Go forth, heed the words of the sleepless watchers, but remember... you are in our world now (tm)!&quot;<br>
<br>
Then you fight phantasms and such? Sure. Maybe as part of some quest to allow you to move on elsewhere? Basically, the IC representation of the OOC mechanic of making sure that the folks heading on to whatever know certain basic tactics?<br>
<br>
Setting this up to get real loot? No. It sounds like a training simulation, not a game.<br>
<br>
We do this in our home game - except we call it &quot;training at the guild hall&quot; or &quot;the jousting tournament at the county fair&quot; or something of that sort that allows our GM to make darn sure we are up to snuff on flanking or attacks of opportunity or threat radius of various weapons or how to handle grappling attacks or whatever. Preferably before we head into that new adventure featuring lots of flanking/AoOs/reach weapons/hill giant mud wrestlers.<br>
<br>
It is a fine thing to put a good roleplay overlay on basic game mechanic familiarization. But don't confuse it with actual roleplay.<br>
<br>
